# ─── Firebase Configuration (required) ────────────────────────────────────
# EcoGuard Finance requires a configured Firebase project. The application
# will not authenticate users or persist applications without these values.
#
# Get these values from: https://console.firebase.google.com
# Project Settings -> General -> Your Apps -> Web App -> SDK setup and configuration

VITE_FIREBASE_API_KEY=your_api_key_here
VITE_FIREBASE_AUTH_DOMAIN=your-project.firebaseapp.com
VITE_FIREBASE_PROJECT_ID=your-project-id
VITE_FIREBASE_STORAGE_BUCKET=your-project.appspot.com
VITE_FIREBASE_MESSAGING_SENDER_ID=000000000000
VITE_FIREBASE_APP_ID=1:000000000000:web:0000000000000000

# ─── Setup notes ───────────────────────────────────────────────────────────
# 1. Copy this file to .env.local (never commit .env.local to git).
# 2. In the Firebase console, enable:
#    - Authentication -> Sign-in method -> Email/Password
#    - Firestore Database (start in production mode and apply the security
#      rules documented in README.md)
# 3. For Railway: add each variable above under your service's Variables tab.
#    Railway injects them at build time (Vite picks up VITE_* prefixed vars).
#
# ─── Assigning the administrator role ─────────────────────────────────────
# There is no client-facing way to create an administrator account, by
# design. New accounts always register with role "applicant". To grant
# administrator access:
#   1. Have the person register a normal account via the app.
#   2. In the Firebase console, open Firestore Database.
#   3. Navigate to the "users" collection and open their document (keyed by
#      their Firebase Auth UID — visible in Authentication -> Users).
#   4. Change the "role" field from "applicant" to "admin", then save.
#   5. The user must sign out and sign back in. They will then see the
#      Admin Portal link in the navigation bar.
